From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: VyOS LS1046A maintainers <ask20@vyos-ls1046a-build>
Date: Tue, 12 May 2026 22:30:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 1/3] crypto: caam/qi: share descriptors with external
 consumers

For the ASK2 fast-path (NXP LS1046A FMan/210 ucode driving an
offline port for IPsec hardware offload, see
specs/ask2-rewrite-spec.md §8.1), an in-kernel consumer needs to
dequeue completed CAAM frames from a chosen sink FQID rather than the
standard per-CPU response FQ that caamalg_qi.c sets up.

Introduce two exported entry points:

    int  caam_qi_ext_consumer_register(struct caam_drv_ctx *ctx,
                                       const char *consumer_name,
                                       u32 sink_fqid,
                                       u32 *caam_req_fqid);
    void caam_qi_ext_consumer_release(struct caam_drv_ctx *ctx);

plus the upstream-ready public header include/linux/crypto/caam_qi_share.h
and small bookkeeping (mutex + bool) on struct caam_drv_ctx.

Implementation strategy mirrors the existing caam_drv_ctx_update() FQ
swap dance:

  1. Allocate a fresh request FQ programmed with @sink_fqid as its
     context_b response target (instead of qman_fq_fqid(rsp_fq)).
  2. Atomically swap ctx->req_fq to the new FQ.
  3. Drain the old request FQ via empty_caam_fq().
  4. Schedule the new FQ; subsequent enqueues land at @sink_fqid.
  5. Kill the old FQ.

create_caam_req_fq() is refactored to take a u32 rsp_fqid (the value
stored in opts.fqd.context_b) instead of a struct qman_fq *rsp_fq, so
the register/release path can pass any FQID, not only the per-CPU
response FQ that caam_drv_ctx_init() picks. Both existing callers
(caam_drv_ctx_update() and caam_drv_ctx_init()) are updated to pass
qman_fq_fqid(drv_ctx->rsp_fq), preserving prior behaviour.

Single-consumer per ctx (returns -EBUSY on second register without an
intervening release). Reference-counted via the existing
ctx->refcnt. Idempotent release (no-op when no consumer is
registered, including NULL/IS_ERR ctx).

No behaviour change for in-tree CAAM users that do not call the new
entry points: qi.c retains identical fast-path semantics; only the
struct grows by sizeof(struct mutex) + sizeof(bool).

Caller-side documentation lives in include/linux/crypto/caam_qi_share.h.

---
diff --git a/drivers/crypto/caam/qi.c b/drivers/crypto/caam/qi.c
index 1e731ed..da5388c 100644
--- a/drivers/crypto/caam/qi.c
+++ b/drivers/crypto/caam/qi.c
@@ -16,6 +16,7 @@
 #include <linux/platform_device.h>
 #include <linux/slab.h>
 #include <linux/string.h>
+#include <linux/crypto/caam_qi_share.h>
 #include <soc/fsl/qman.h>
 
 #include "debugfs.h"
@@ -173,7 +174,7 @@ static void caam_fq_ern_cb(struct qman_portal *qm, struct qman_fq *fq,
 }
 
 static struct qman_fq *create_caam_req_fq(struct device *qidev,
-					  struct qman_fq *rsp_fq,
+					  u32 rsp_fqid,
 					  dma_addr_t hwdesc,
 					  int fq_sched_flag)
 {
@@ -201,7 +202,7 @@ static struct qman_fq *create_caam_req_fq(struct device *qidev,
 				   QM_INITFQ_WE_CONTEXTA | QM_INITFQ_WE_CGID);
 	opts.fqd.fq_ctrl = cpu_to_be16(QM_FQCTRL_CPCSTASH | QM_FQCTRL_CGE);
 	qm_fqd_set_destwq(&opts.fqd, qm_channel_caam, 2);
-	opts.fqd.context_b = cpu_to_be32(qman_fq_fqid(rsp_fq));
+	opts.fqd.context_b = cpu_to_be32(rsp_fqid);
 	qm_fqd_context_a_set64(&opts.fqd, hwdesc);
 	opts.fqd.cgid = qipriv.cgr.cgrid;
 
@@ -340,7 +341,8 @@ int caam_drv_ctx_update(struct caam_drv_ctx *drv_ctx, u32 *sh_desc)
 	old_fq = drv_ctx->req_fq;
 
 	/* Create a new req FQ in parked state */
-	new_fq = create_caam_req_fq(drv_ctx->qidev, drv_ctx->rsp_fq,
+	new_fq = create_caam_req_fq(drv_ctx->qidev,
+				    qman_fq_fqid(drv_ctx->rsp_fq),
 				    drv_ctx->context_a, 0);
 	if (IS_ERR(new_fq)) {
 		dev_err(qidev, "FQ allocation for shdesc update failed\n");
@@ -452,7 +454,9 @@ struct caam_drv_ctx *caam_drv_ctx_init(struct device *qidev,
 	drv_ctx->rsp_fq = per_cpu(pcpu_qipriv.rsp_fq, drv_ctx->cpu);
 
 	/* Attach request FQ */
-	drv_ctx->req_fq = create_caam_req_fq(qidev, drv_ctx->rsp_fq, hwdesc,
+	drv_ctx->req_fq = create_caam_req_fq(qidev,
+					     qman_fq_fqid(drv_ctx->rsp_fq),
+					     hwdesc,
 					     QMAN_INITFQ_FLAG_SCHED);
 	if (IS_ERR(drv_ctx->req_fq)) {
 		dev_err(qidev, "create_caam_req_fq failed\n");
@@ -464,6 +468,10 @@ struct caam_drv_ctx *caam_drv_ctx_init(struct device *qidev,
 	/* init reference counter used to track references to request FQ */
 	refcount_set(&drv_ctx->refcnt, 1);
 
+	/* External-consumer (caam_qi_ext_consumer_register) bookkeeping. */
+	mutex_init(&drv_ctx->ext_lock);
+	drv_ctx->ext_active = false;
+
 	drv_ctx->qidev = qidev;
 	return drv_ctx;
 }
@@ -811,3 +819,170 @@ free_cpumask:
 fail_cpumask:
 	return err;
 }
+
+/*
+ * --------------------------------------------------------------------
+ * External-consumer descriptor sharing (CAAM/QI <-> non-crypto-API)
+ * --------------------------------------------------------------------
+ *
+ * See include/linux/crypto/caam_qi_share.h for the public contract.
+ *
+ * Implementation strategy: mirror caam_drv_ctx_update() FQ-swap dance.
+ *
+ * 1. Allocate a new request FQ programmed with @sink_fqid (instead of
+ *    the per-CPU rsp_fq->fqid) as its response target via context_b.
+ * 2. Park-and-empty the old request FQ. In-flight responses already on
+ *    the old per-CPU rsp_fq path drain naturally.
+ * 3. Atomically swap ctx->req_fq to the new FQ.
+ * 4. Schedule the new FQ. Subsequent enqueues land at @sink_fqid.
+ */
+int caam_qi_ext_consumer_register(struct caam_drv_ctx *ctx,
+				  const char *consumer_name,
+				  u32 sink_fqid,
+				  u32 *caam_req_fqid)
+{
+	struct qman_fq *new_fq, *old_fq;
+	struct device *qidev;
+	int ret;
+
+	if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(ctx) || !consumer_name || !caam_req_fqid ||
+	    sink_fqid == 0)
+		return -EINVAL;
+
+	qidev = ctx->qidev;
+
+	mutex_lock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+
+	if (ctx->ext_active) {
+		dev_dbg(qidev,
+			"caam_qi: ext_consumer already registered on ctx %px\n",
+			ctx);
+		mutex_unlock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+		return -EBUSY;
+	}
+
+	old_fq = ctx->req_fq;
+
+	new_fq = create_caam_req_fq(qidev, sink_fqid, ctx->context_a, 0);
+	if (IS_ERR(new_fq)) {
+		ret = PTR_ERR(new_fq);
+		dev_err(qidev,
+			"caam_qi: ext_consumer FQ alloc failed for %s: %d\n",
+			consumer_name, ret);
+		mutex_unlock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+		return ret;
+	}
+
+	/* Hook up new FQ so subsequent enqueues queue against it. */
+	ctx->req_fq = new_fq;
+
+	/* Drain the old req FQ. Same pattern as caam_drv_ctx_update(). */
+	ret = empty_caam_fq(old_fq, ctx);
+	if (ret) {
+		dev_err(qidev,
+			"caam_qi: failed to drain old req FQ for %s: %d\n",
+			consumer_name, ret);
+		ctx->req_fq = old_fq;
+		if (kill_fq(qidev, new_fq))
+			dev_warn(qidev,
+				 "caam_qi: ext_consumer new FQ kill failed\n");
+		mutex_unlock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+		return ret;
+	}
+
+	ret = qman_schedule_fq(new_fq);
+	if (ret) {
+		dev_err(qidev,
+			"caam_qi: failed to schedule ext_consumer FQ for %s: %d\n",
+			consumer_name, ret);
+		ctx->req_fq = old_fq;
+		if (kill_fq(qidev, new_fq))
+			dev_warn(qidev,
+				 "caam_qi: ext_consumer new FQ kill failed\n");
+		mutex_unlock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+		return ret;
+	}
+
+	if (kill_fq(qidev, old_fq))
+		dev_warn(qidev,
+			 "caam_qi: ext_consumer old FQ kill failed (leaking)\n");
+
+	ctx->ext_active = true;
+	refcount_inc(&ctx->refcnt);
+
+	*caam_req_fqid = qman_fq_fqid(new_fq);
+
+	dev_dbg(qidev,
+		"caam_qi: ext_consumer %s installed: req_fqid=%u sink_fqid=%u\n",
+		consumer_name, *caam_req_fqid, sink_fqid);
+
+	mutex_unlock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+	return 0;
+}
+EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(caam_qi_ext_consumer_register);
+
+void caam_qi_ext_consumer_release(struct caam_drv_ctx *ctx)
+{
+	struct qman_fq *new_fq, *old_fq;
+	struct device *qidev;
+	int ret;
+
+	if (IS_ERR_OR_NULL(ctx))
+		return;
+
+	qidev = ctx->qidev;
+
+	mutex_lock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+
+	if (!ctx->ext_active) {
+		mutex_unlock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+		return;
+	}
+
+	old_fq = ctx->req_fq;
+
+	/*
+	 * Restore the default per-CPU response path: re-create the request
+	 * FQ with rsp_fq->fqid as its context_b target. Same swap dance.
+	 */
+	new_fq = create_caam_req_fq(qidev, qman_fq_fqid(ctx->rsp_fq),
+				    ctx->context_a, 0);
+	if (IS_ERR(new_fq)) {
+		dev_err(qidev,
+			"caam_qi: ext_consumer release: req FQ realloc failed: %ld\n",
+			PTR_ERR(new_fq));
+		/*
+		 * Cannot revert cleanly. Leave ext_active=true so a retry is
+		 * possible without double-decrementing the refcount.
+		 */
+		mutex_unlock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+		return;
+	}
+
+	ctx->req_fq = new_fq;
+
+	ret = empty_caam_fq(old_fq, ctx);
+	if (ret)
+		dev_warn(qidev,
+			 "caam_qi: ext_consumer release: drain failed: %d\n",
+			 ret);
+
+	if (qman_schedule_fq(new_fq))
+		dev_warn(qidev,
+			 "caam_qi: ext_consumer release: schedule new FQ failed\n");
+
+	if (kill_fq(qidev, old_fq))
+		dev_warn(qidev,
+			 "caam_qi: ext_consumer release: old FQ kill failed\n");
+
+	ctx->ext_active = false;
+
+	dev_dbg(qidev,
+		"caam_qi: ext_consumer released, req_fqid restored to %u\n",
+		qman_fq_fqid(new_fq));
+
+	mutex_unlock(&ctx->ext_lock);
+
+	refcount_dec(&ctx->refcnt);
+}
+EXPORT_SYMBOL_GPL(caam_qi_ext_consumer_release);
diff --git a/drivers/crypto/caam/qi.h b/drivers/crypto/caam/qi.h
index a96e3d2..68b1461 100644
--- a/drivers/crypto/caam/qi.h
+++ b/drivers/crypto/caam/qi.h
@@ -11,6 +11,7 @@
 
 #include <crypto/algapi.h>
 #include <linux/compiler_attributes.h>
+#include <linux/mutex.h>
 #include <soc/fsl/qman.h>
 #include "compat.h"
 #include "desc.h"
@@ -71,6 +72,13 @@ struct caam_drv_ctx {
 	int cpu;
 	enum optype op_type;
 	struct device *qidev;
+	/* External-consumer support (caam_qi_ext_consumer_register).
+	 * @ext_lock serialises register/release/update against each other.
+	 * @ext_active is true while a non-callback (sink-FQID) consumer
+	 * owns the response path of this ctx.
+	 */
+	struct mutex ext_lock;
+	bool ext_active;
 };
 
 /**
diff --git a/include/linux/crypto/caam_qi_share.h b/include/linux/crypto/caam_qi_share.h
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..23fac98
--- /dev/null
+++ b/include/linux/crypto/caam_qi_share.h
@@ -0,0 +1,94 @@
+/* SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-2.0 */
+/*
+ * CAAM/QI external descriptor sharing.
+ *
+ * Allows an in-kernel consumer (e.g. NXP LS1046A FMan 210 ucode driving
+ * an offline port for IPsec hardware fast-path) to dequeue completed
+ * frames from a CAAM/QI request context's response side directly,
+ * instead of going through the standard kernel-crypto-API callback.
+ *
+ * The CAAM driver context is created in the normal way (via
+ * caam_drv_ctx_init() out of caamalg_qi.c). After registration the
+ * CAAM hardware is reprogrammed to enqueue completed frames to a
+ * caller-supplied sink FQID instead of the per-CPU response FQ.
+ *
+ * Single-consumer per ctx. Reference-counted. Idempotent release.
+ *
+ * See specs/ask2-rewrite-spec.md §8.1 (vyos-ls1046a-build) for the
+ * design rationale.
+ *
+ * Copyright 2026 Mono Networks / VyOS LS1046A maintainers.
+ */
+
+#ifndef _LINUX_CRYPTO_CAAM_QI_SHARE_H
+#define _LINUX_CRYPTO_CAAM_QI_SHARE_H
+
+#include <linux/types.h>
+
+struct caam_drv_ctx;
+
+/**
+ * caam_qi_ext_consumer_register - share a CAAM/QI descriptor's response path
+ *				   with an external dequeuer.
+ * @ctx:		descriptor context previously created via
+ *			caam_drv_ctx_init() (typically by caamalg_qi.c on
+ *			behalf of an xfrm SA install).
+ * @consumer_name:	diagnostic string for tracepoints / dev_dbg, e.g.
+ *			"ask:fman0:op1:spi-0x12345678". Must be non-NULL.
+ * @sink_fqid:		FQID that CAAM should enqueue completed (response)
+ *			frames to. Caller-owned (typically a 210-managed
+ *			FMan offline-port RX FQ). REPLACES the per-CPU
+ *			response path; while an external consumer is
+ *			registered, in-kernel crypto-API callers of @ctx will
+ *			NOT receive completions via the normal callback.
+ * @caam_req_fqid:	[out] FQID of the CAAM request queue that the
+ *			external producer (e.g. FMan 210 ucode) must enqueue
+ *			encrypted ESP frames to. This is the request FQ's
+ *			current FQID, exposed read-only to the caller. May
+ *			change across register/release cycles (see Notes).
+ *
+ * Single-consumer: returns -EBUSY if @ctx already has an external
+ * consumer registered.
+ *
+ * Refcount: increments @ctx->refcnt on success. The caller must invoke
+ * caam_qi_ext_consumer_release() to balance it.
+ *
+ * Notes:
+ * - Implementation parks the existing request FQ, allocates a fresh one
+ *   programmed with sink_fqid as its response target, and atomically
+ *   swaps it in (mirroring caam_drv_ctx_update()). The new FQ has a
+ *   different (dynamically allocated) FQID; that is the FQID returned
+ *   in *@caam_req_fqid.
+ * - Frames already in flight when this is called complete on the OLD
+ *   response path; only frames enqueued after the swap reach
+ *   @sink_fqid.
+ * - Caller is responsible for any synchronisation needed against the
+ *   external dequeuer when sink_fqid is shared (e.g. parking the FMan
+ *   offline port before release).
+ *
+ * Return: 0 on success, -EINVAL on bad arguments, -EBUSY if an external
+ * consumer is already registered, -ENOMEM on allocation failure, or any
+ * negative errno propagated from the underlying QMan FQ operations.
+ */
+int caam_qi_ext_consumer_register(struct caam_drv_ctx *ctx,
+				  const char *consumer_name,
+				  u32 sink_fqid,
+				  u32 *caam_req_fqid);
+
+/**
+ * caam_qi_ext_consumer_release - undo caam_qi_ext_consumer_register().
+ * @ctx: descriptor context that was previously registered.
+ *
+ * Restores the default per-CPU response path so subsequent
+ * caam_qi_enqueue() calls on @ctx are dispatched to the normal
+ * caam_qi_cbk callback again.
+ *
+ * Idempotent: a no-op if no external consumer is currently registered
+ * on @ctx (or if @ctx is NULL / IS_ERR).
+ *
+ * In-flight frames already queued on the previous sink FQ are NOT
+ * retroactively redirected. Decrements @ctx->refcnt.
+ */
+void caam_qi_ext_consumer_release(struct caam_drv_ctx *ctx);
+
+#endif /* _LINUX_CRYPTO_CAAM_QI_SHARE_H */
-- 
